div.p:
          Receptarium (P.Mich. inv. 21 = P.Mich. 17.758). Thirteen pages from a papyrus codex, written on both sides, containing a collection of therapeutic prescriptions.
The codex was probably commissioned by its owner, a practicing physician, who considerably expanded it with additional recipes written in the bottom margins, corrections to the main text, and personal annotations on the employment of the prescriptions (e.g. H,8-9). The owner's corrections, in a faster and smaller hand, are quite distinguishable from those made by the first copyist (hand 1). Many other errors remained uncorrected, giving us the impression of a quick, careless copy.
The prescriptions are paralleled by literary examples, and are composed in the common, fourfold format consisting of title (
          prographe
          ), indication of destination (
          epangelia
          ), enumeration of the ingredients (
          synthesis
          ), and method of preparation (
          skeuasia
          ). Each heading is written in eisthesis; some preparations are named, as usual, after their creator (Azanites - B,2; Dionysius - C,8; Heras - E,5; Telamon - E,9-15; Hygienus - D,4). The organizing principle seems to be according to type of medication, with pills and lozenges preceding wet and dry plasters (see a similar arrangement in Gal.
          Comp.med.sec.loc.
          13.116-27 K); the current alphabetical denomination (A-M) does not follow the original articulation of the work (the most likely, true arrangment would be Ir-v, Jr-v, Lv-r, Gr-v, Hr-v, Kr-v, Mr-v, A-F).
